, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Musters","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: locative name from Les Moutiers-Hubert (Calvados)."],"variants":[{"name":"Muster","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Franz, Hans, Bernhard, Heinz.","German: occupational name for a producer or seller of ‘most’, unfermented grape juice, fruit wine, from Middle Low German <i>must, most</i>, Middle High German <i>most</i> (see   Most  ).","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Mostar</b> (see   Moster  ), a cognate of 4 below."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Musters was born about 1115, in Kirklington, Yorkshire, England, his father, Geoffrey de Musters, was 37 and his mother, Mrs. Geoffrey de Masters, was 34. He married Mary de Rievers before 1145, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died after 1183, in Kirklington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1115–after 1183":"umbes 1115–pärast 1183","1115–1183":"1115–1183","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","1124–1194":"1124–1194","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","1145–1228":"1145–1228","–1219":"–1219","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1083–Female":"1083–Surnud","1080":"1080","before 1145":"enne 1145","after 1183":"pärast 1183","1141":"1141","1194":"1194","1183":"1183","1083":"1083","1228":"1228","1115":"1115","1124":"1124","1145":"1145","about 1115":"umbes 1115","about 1145":"umbes 1145","about 1124":"umbes 1124","about 1141":"umbes 1141","1219":"1219","Kirklington, Yorkshire, England":"Kirklington, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Kirklington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kirklington, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1115–after 1183":"noin 1115–1183 jälkeen","1115–1183":"1115–1183","1115–Female":"1115–Kuollut","1124–1194":"1124–1194","1141–Male":"1141–Kuollut","1145–1228":"1145–1228","–1219":"–1219","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","1083–Female":"1083–Kuollut","1080":"1080","before 1145":"ennen vuotta 1145","after 1183":"1183 jälkeen","1141":"1141","1194":"1194","1183":"1183","1083":"1083","1228":"1228","1115":"1115","1124":"1124"